L and back again. In affected versions this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker has sufficient rights to execute commands of the host only by manipulating the processed input stream. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types. XStream 1.4.18 uses no longer a blacklist by default, since it cannot be secured for general purpose.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"CVE-2021-39151 (sca)","name":"Cve202139151","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"XStream is a simple library that serializes objects to XML and back again. In versions prior to 1.4.18, this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to load and execute arbitrary code from a remote host only by manipulating the processed input stream. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types. XStream 1.4.18 no longer uses a blacklist by default, since it cannot be secured for general purposes.","markdown":"XStream is a simple library that serializes objects to XML and back again. In versions prior to 1.4.18, this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to load and execute arbitrary code from a remote host only by manipulating the processed input stream. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types. XStream 1.4.18 no longer uses a blacklist by default, since it cannot be secured for general purposes."},"fullDescription":{"text":"XStream is a simple library that serializes objects to XML and back again. In versions prior to 1.4.18, this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to load and execute arbitrary code from a remote host only by manipulating the processed input stream. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types. XStream 1.4.18 no longer uses a blacklist by default, since it cannot be secured for general purposes."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202139151","id":"CVE-2021-39151 (sca)","description":"XStream is a simple library that serializes objects to XML and back again. In versions prior to 1.4.18, this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to load and execute arbitrary code from a remote host only by manipulating the processed input stream. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types. XStream 1.4.18 no longer uses a blacklist by default, since it cannot be secured for general purposes.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"CVE-2021-39150 (sca)","name":"Cve202139150","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"XStream is a simple library to serialize objects to XML and back again. In affected versions, this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to request data from internal resources that are not publicly available only by manipulating the processed input stream with a Java runtime version 14 to 8. Users who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types are not affected by this vulnerability. If you rely on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist of the Security Framework you are vulnerable in com.thoughtworks.xstream:xstream versions prior to 1.4.18.","markdown":"XStream is a simple library to serialize objects to XML and back again. In affected versions, this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to request data from internal resources that are not publicly available only by manipulating the processed input stream with a Java runtime version 14 to 8. Users who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types are not affected by this vulnerability. If you rely on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist of the Security Framework you are vulnerable in com.thoughtworks.xstream:xstream versions prior to 1.4.18."},"fullDescription":{"text":"XStream is a simple library to serialize objects to XML and back again. In affected versions, this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to request data from internal resources that are not publicly available only by manipulating the processed input stream with a Java runtime version 14 to 8. Users who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types are not affected by this vulnerability. If you rely on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist of the Security Framework you are vulnerable in com.thoughtworks.xstream:xstream versions prior to 1.4.18."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202139150","id":"CVE-2021-39150 (sca)","description":"XStream is a simple library to serialize objects to XML and back again. In affected versions, this vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to request data from internal resources that are not publicly available only by manipulating the processed input stream with a Java runtime version 14 to 8. Users who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s security framework with a whitelist limited to the minimal required types are not affected by this vulnerability. If you rely on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist of the Security Framework you are vulnerable in com.thoughtworks.xstream:xstream versions prior to 1.4.18.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"SSRF - 15179929566605030594 (sast)","name":"SSRF","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The application sends a request to a remote server, for some resource, using openStream in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/ssrf/SSRFTask2.java:54. However, an attacker can control the target of the request, by sending a URL or other data in url at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/ssrf/SSRFTask2.java:47.\n\n","markdown":"The application sends a request to a remote server, for some resource, using openStream in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/ssrf/SSRFTask2.java:54. However, an attacker can control the target of the request, by sending a URL or other data in url at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/ssrf/SSRFTask2.java:47.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The application sends a request to a remote server, for some resource, using openStream in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/ssrf/SSRFTask2.java:54. However, an attacker can control the target of the request, by sending a URL or other data in url at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/ssrf/SSRFTask2.java:47.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"SSRF","id":"SSRF - 15179929566605030594 (sast)","description":"The application sends a request to a remote server, for some resource, using openStream in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/ssrf/SSRFTask2.java:54. However, an attacker can control the target of the request, by sending a URL or other data in url at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/ssrf/SSRFTask2.java:47.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"CVE-2024-12798 (sca)","name":"Cve202412798","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Arbitrary Code Execution vulnerability in \u0026#34;JaninoEventEvaluator\u0026#34; by QOS.CH logback in Java applications, allows attackers to execute arbitrary code by compromising an existing logback configuration file or by injecting an environment variable before program execution. Malicious logback configuration files can allow the attacker to execute arbitrary code using the \u0026#34;JaninoEventEvaluator\u0026#34; extension. A successful attack requires the user to have write access to a configuration file. Alternatively, the attacker could inject a malicious environment variable pointing to a malicious configuration file. In both cases, the attack requires existing privilege. This issue affects ch.qos.logback:logback-classic and ch.qos.logback:logback-core packages versions through 1.3.14, and 1.4.0 through 1.5.12.","markdown":"Arbitrary Code Execution vulnerability in \u0026#34;JaninoEventEvaluator\u0026#34; by QOS.CH logback in Java applications, allows attackers to execute arbitrary code by compromising an existing logback configuration file or by injecting an environment variable before program execution. Malicious logback configuration files can allow the attacker to execute arbitrary code using the \u0026#34;JaninoEventEvaluator\u0026#34; extension. A successful attack requires the user to have write access to a configuration file. Alternatively, the attacker could inject a malicious environment variable pointing to a malicious configuration file. In both cases, the attack requires existing privilege. This issue affects ch.qos.logback:logback-classic and ch.qos.logback:logback-core packages versions through 1.3.14, and 1.4.0 through 1.5.12."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Arbitrary Code Execution vulnerability in \u0026#34;JaninoEventEvaluator\u0026#34; by QOS.CH logback in Java applications, allows attackers to execute arbitrary code by compromising an existing logback configuration file or by injecting an environment variable before program execution. Malicious logback configuration files can allow the attacker to execute arbitrary code using the \u0026#34;JaninoEventEvaluator\u0026#34; extension. A successful attack requires the user to have write access to a configuration file. Alternatively, the attacker could inject a malicious environment variable pointing to a malicious configuration file. In both cases, the attack requires existing privilege. This issue affects ch.qos.logback:logback-classic and ch.qos.logback:logback-core packages versions through 1.3.14, and 1.4.0 through 1.5.12."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202412798","id":"CVE-2024-12798 (sca)","description":"Arbitrary Code Execution vulnerability in \u0026#34;JaninoEventEvaluator\u0026#34; by QOS.CH logback in Java applications, allows attackers to execute arbitrary code by compromising an existing logback configuration file or by injecting an environment variable before program execution. Malicious logback configuration files can allow the attacker to execute arbitrary code using the \u0026#34;JaninoEventEvaluator\u0026#34; extension. A successful attack requires the user to have write access to a configuration file. Alternatively, the attacker could inject a malicious environment variable pointing to a malicious configuration file. In both cases, the attack requires existing privilege. This issue affects ch.qos.logback:logback-classic and ch.qos.logback:logback-core packages versions through 1.3.14, and 1.4.0 through 1.5.12.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"JWT Use Of Hardcoded Secret - 2420793684363197756 (sast)","name":"JWT Use Of Hardcoded Secret","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The variable \u0026#34;\u0026#34;qwertyqwerty1234\u0026#34;\u0026#34; at line 44 of file /WebGoat-main/src/test/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/TokenTest.java is assigned with a hardcoded, literal value. This value is used as the secret key to sign the JWTs.\n\n","markdown":"The variable \u0026#34;\u0026#34;qwertyqwerty1234\u0026#34;\u0026#34; at line 44 of file /WebGoat-main/src/test/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/TokenTest.java is assigned with a hardcoded, literal value. This value is used as the secret key to sign the JWTs.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The variable \u0026#34;\u0026#34;qwertyqwerty1234\u0026#34;\u0026#34; at line 44 of file /WebGoat-main/src/test/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/TokenTest.java is assigned with a hardcoded, literal value. This value is used as the secret key to sign the JWTs.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"JWT Use Of Hardcoded Secret","id":"JWT Use Of Hardcoded Secret - 2420793684363197756 (sast)","description":"The variable \u0026#34;\u0026#34;qwertyqwerty1234\u0026#34;\u0026#34; at line 44 of file /WebGoat-main/src/test/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/TokenTest.java is assigned with a hardcoded, literal value. This value is used as the secret key to sign the JWTs.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"CVE-2020-11023 (sca)","name":"Cve202011023","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"In jQuery versions 1.0.3 through 3.4.1, passing HTML containing \u0026lt;option\u0026gt; elements from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery\u0026#39;s DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This vulnerability also affects jquery-rails versions through 4.3.5.","markdown":"In jQuery versions 1.0.3 through 3.4.1, passing HTML containing \u0026lt;option\u0026gt; elements from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery\u0026#39;s DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This vulnerability also affects jquery-rails versions through 4.3.5."},"fullDescription":{"text":"In jQuery versions 1.0.3 through 3.4.1, passing HTML containing \u0026lt;option\u0026gt; elements from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery\u0026#39;s DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This vulnerability also affects jquery-rails versions through 4.3.5."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202011023","id":"CVE-2020-11023 (sca)","description":"In jQuery versions 1.0.3 through 3.4.1, passing HTML containing \u0026lt;option\u0026gt; elements from untrusted sources - even after sanitizing it - to one of jQuery\u0026#39;s DOM manipulation methods (i.e. .html(), .append(), and others) may execute untrusted code. This vulnerability also affects jquery-rails versions through 4.3.5.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"HttpOnly Cookie Flag Not Set - 15287255134376319324 (sast)","name":"HttpOnly Cookie Flag Not Set","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The web application\u0026#39;s login method creates a cookie cookie, at line 132 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/JWTVotesEndpoint.java, and returns it in the response. However, the application is not configured to automatically set the cookie with the \u0026#34;httpOnly\u0026#34; attribute, and the code does not explicitly add this to the cookie.\n\n","markdown":"The web application\u0026#39;s login method creates a cookie cookie, at line 132 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/JWTVotesEndpoint.java, and returns it in the response. However, the application is not configured to automatically set the cookie with the \u0026#34;httpOnly\u0026#34; attribute, and the code does not explicitly add this to the cookie.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The web application\u0026#39;s login method creates a cookie cookie, at line 132 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/JWTVotesEndpoint.java, and returns it in the response. However, the application is not configured to automatically set the cookie with the \u0026#34;httpOnly\u0026#34; attribute, and the code does not explicitly add this to the cookie.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"HttpOnly Cookie Flag Not Set","id":"HttpOnly Cookie Flag Not Set - 15287255134376319324 (sast)","description":"The web app