4417 (sast)","name":"Secure Cookie Flag Not Set","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/JWTVotesEndpoint.java application configuration file, at line 133, does not define sensitive application cookies with the \u0026#34;secure\u0026#34; flag, which could cause the client to send those cookies in plaintext over an insecure network communication (HTTP). This may lead to a Session Hijacking attack.\n\n","markdown":"The /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/JWTVotesEndpoint.java application configuration file, at line 133, does not define sensitive application cookies with the \u0026#34;secure\u0026#34; flag, which could cause the client to send those cookies in plaintext over an insecure network communication (HTTP). This may lead to a Session Hijacking attack.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/JWTVotesEndpoint.java application configuration file, at line 133, does not define sensitive application cookies with the \u0026#34;secure\u0026#34; flag, which could cause the client to send those cookies in plaintext over an insecure network communication (HTTP). This may lead to a Session Hijacking attack.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Secure Cookie Flag Not Set","id":"Secure Cookie Flag Not Set - 17656269117524994417 (sast)","description":"The /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/jwt/JWTVotesEndpoint.java application configuration file, at line 133, does not define sensitive application cookies with the \u0026#34;secure\u0026#34; flag, which could cause the client to send those cookies in plaintext over an insecure network communication (HTTP). This may lead to a Session Hijacking attack.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Unsafe Object Binding - 18167789603095321044 (sast)","name":"Unsafe Object Binding","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The userForm at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/users/RegistrationController.java in line 35 may unintentionally allow setting the value of save in addUser, in the object /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/users/UserService.java at line 45.\n\n","markdown":"The userForm at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/users/RegistrationController.java in line 35 may unintentionally allow setting the value of save in addUser, in the object /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/users/UserService.java at line 45.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The userForm at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/users/RegistrationController.java in line 35 may unintentionally allow setting the value of save in addUser, in the object /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/users/UserService.java at line 45.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Unsafe Object Binding","id":"Unsafe Object Binding - 18167789603095321044 (sast)","description":"The userForm at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/users/RegistrationController.java in line 35 may unintentionally allow setting the value of save in addUser, in the object /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/users/UserService.java at line 45.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Use of a One Way Hash with a Predictable Salt - 2301179517126599776 (sast)","name":"Use of a One Way Hash with a Predictable Salt","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The application protects passwords with digest in genUserHash, of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/DisplayUser.java at line 59, using a cryptographic hash PASSWORD_SALT_SIMPLE. However, the code does not salt the hash with an unpredictable, random value, allowing an attacker to reverse the hash value.","markdown":"The application protects passwords with digest in genUserHash, of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/DisplayUser.java at line 59, using a cryptographic hash PASSWORD_SALT_SIMPLE. However, the code does not salt the hash with an unpredictable, random value, allowing an attacker to reverse the hash value."},"fullDescription":{"text":"The application protects passwords with digest in genUserHash, of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/DisplayUser.java at line 59, using a cryptographic hash PASSWORD_SALT_SIMPLE. However, the code does not salt the hash with an unpredictable, random value, allowing an attacker to reverse the hash value."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Use of a One Way Hash with a Predictable Salt","id":"Use of a One Way Hash with a Predictable Salt - 2301179517126599776 (sast)","description":"The application protects passwords with digest in genUserHash, of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/DisplayUser.java at line 59, using a cryptographic hash PASSWORD_SALT_SIMPLE. However, the code does not salt the hash with an unpredictable, random value, allowing an attacker to reverse the hash value.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"CVE-2015-9251 (sca)","name":"Cve20159251","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"jQuery before 3.0.0-beta1 is vulnerable to Cross-site Scripting (XSS) attacks when a cross-domain Ajax request is performed without the dataType option, causing text/javascript responses to be executed.","markdown":"jQuery before 3.0.0-beta1 is vulnerable to Cross-site Scripting (XSS) attacks when a cross-domain Ajax request is performed without the dataType option, causing text/javascript responses to be executed."},"fullDescription":{"text":"jQuery before 3.0.0-beta1 is vulnerable to Cross-site Scripting (XSS) attacks when a cross-domain Ajax request is performed without the dataType option, causing text/javascript responses to be executed."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20159251","id":"CVE-2015-9251 (sca)","description":"jQuery before 3.0.0-beta1 is vulnerable to Cross-site Scripting (XSS) attacks when a cross-domain Ajax request is performed without the dataType option, causing text/javascript responses to be executed.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-55668 (sca)","name":"Cve202555668","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Session Fixation vulnerability in Apache Tomcat via rewrite valve. This issue affects org.apache.tomcat:tomcat-catalina: versions from 8.0.0-RC1 through 8.0.53, 8.5.0 through 8.5.100, 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.105, 10.1.0-M1 through 10.1.41 and 11.0.0-M1 through 11.0.7.","markdown":"Session Fixation vulnerability in Apache Tomcat via rewrite valve. This issue affects org.apache.tomcat:tomcat-catalina: versions from 8.0.0-RC1 through 8.0.53, 8.5.0 through 8.5.100, 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.105, 10.1.0-M1 through 10.1.41 and 11.0.0-M1 through 11.0.7."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Session Fixation vulnerability in Apache Tomcat via rewrite valve. This issue affects org.apache.tomcat:tomcat-catalina: versions from 8.0.0-RC1 through 8.0.53, 8.5.0 through 8.5.100, 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.105, 10.1.0-M1 through 10.1.41 and 11.0.0-M1 through 11.0.7."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202555668","id":"CVE-2025-55668 (sca)","description":"Session Fixation vulnerability in Apache Tomcat via rewrite valve. This issue affects org.apache.tomcat:tomcat-catalina: versions from 8.0.0-RC1 through 8.0.53, 8.5.0 through 8.5.100, 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.105, 10.1.0-M1 through 10.1.41 and 11.0.0-M1 through 11.0.7.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"Parameter Tampering - 7096281910242735216 (sast)","name":"Parameter Tampering","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Method usersFixed at line 83 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java gets user input from element username. This input is later used by the application directly as a parameter in a Create, Read, Update, or Delete (CRUD) operation, without being validated. The application then uses this input in method findByUsername to access the database query, at line 29 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingAccessControlUserRepository.java, without any additional server-side filtering or verification. This could allow the user to tamper with the parameter to attempt unauthorized access or manipulate which records are created, read, updated, or deleted.\n\n","markdown":"Method usersFixed at line 83 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java gets user input from element username. This input is later used by the application directly as a parameter in a Create, Read, Update, or Delete (CRUD) operation, without being validated. The application then uses this input in method findByUsername to access the database query, at line 29 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingAccessControlUserRepository.java, without any additional server-side filtering or verification. This could allow the user to tamper with the parameter to attempt unauthorized access or manipulate which records are created, read, updated, or deleted.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Method usersFixed at line 83 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java gets user input from element username. This input is later used by the application directly as a parameter in a Create, Read, Update, or Delete (CRUD) operation, without being validated. The application then uses this input in method findByUsername to access the database query, at line 29 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingAccessControlUserRepository.java, without any additional server-side filtering or verification. This could allow the user to tamper with the parameter to attempt unauthorized access or manipulate which records are created, read, updated, or deleted.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Parameter Tampering","id":"Parameter Tampering - 7096281910242735216 (sast)","description":"Method usersFixed at line 83 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java gets user input from element username. This input is later used by the application directly as a parameter in a Create, Read, Update, or Delete (CRUD) operation, without being validated. The application then uses this input in method findByUsername to access the database query, at line 29 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingAccessControlUserRepository.java, without any additional server-side filtering or verification. This could allow the user to tamper with the parameter to attempt unauthorized access or manipulate which records are created, read, updated, or deleted.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"CVE-2024-12133 (containers)","name":"Cve202412133","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A flaw in libtasn1 causes inefficient handling of specific certificate data. When processing a large number of elements in a certificate, libtasn1 takes much longer than expected, which can slow down or even crash the system. This flaw allows an attacker to send a specially crafted certificate, causing a denial of service attack.","markdown":"A flaw in libtasn1 causes inefficient handling of specific certificate data. When processing a large number of elements in a certificate, libtasn1 takes much longer than expected, which can slow down or even crash the system. This flaw allows an attacker to send a specially crafted certificate, causing a denial of service attack."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A flaw in libtasn1 causes inefficient handling of specific certificate data. When processing a large number of elements in a certificate, libtasn1 takes much longer than expected, which can slow down or even crash the system. This flaw allows an attacker to send a specially crafted certificate, causing a denial of service attack."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202412133","id":"CVE-2024-12133 (containers)","description":"A flaw in libtasn1 causes inefficient handling of specific certificate data. When processing a large number of elements in a certificate, libtasn1 takes much longer than expected, which can slow down or even crash the system. This flaw allows an attacker to send a specially crafted certificate, causing a denial of service attack.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-5702 (containers)","name":"Cve20255702","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The \u0026#34;strcmp\u0026#34; implementation optimized for the Power10 processor in the GNU C Library version 2.39 and later writes to vector registers v20 to v31 without saving contents from the caller (those registers are defined as non-volatile registers by the powerpc64le ABI), resulting in overwriting of its contents and potentially altering control flow of the caller, or leaking the input strings to the function to other parts of the program.","markdown":"The \u0026#34;strcmp\u0026#34; implementation optimized for the Power10 processor in the GNU C Library version 2.39 and later writes to vector registers v20 to v31 without saving contents from the caller (those registers are defined as non-volatile registers by the powerpc64le ABI), resulting in overwriting of its contents and potentially altering control flow of the caller, or leaking the input strings to the function to other parts of the program."},"fullDescription":{"text":"The \u0026#34;strcmp\u0026#34; implementation optimized for the Power10 processor in the GNU C Library version 2.39 and later writes to vector registers v20 to v31 without saving contents from the caller (those registers are defined as non-volatile registers by the powerpc64le ABI), resulting in overwriting of its contents and potentially altering control flow of the caller, or leaking the input strings to the function to other parts of the program."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20255702","id":"CVE-2025-5702 (containers)","description":"The \u0026#34;strcmp\u0026#34; implementation optimized for the Power10 processor in the GNU C Library version 2.39 and later writes to vector registers v20 to v31 without saving contents from the caller (those registers are defined as non-volatile registers by the powerpc64le ABI), resulting in overwriting of its contents and potentially altering control flow of the caller, or leaking the input strings to the function to other parts of the program.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-3277 (containers)","name":"Cve20253277","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"An integer overflow can be triggered in SQLite\u0026#39;s `concat_ws()` function in versions prior to 3.44.4 and 3.45.0 through 3.49.0. The resulting, truncated integer is then used to allocate a buffer. When SQLite then writes the resulting string to the buffer, it uses the original, untruncated size and thus a wild Heap Buffer overflow of size ~4GB can be triggered. This can result in arbitrary code execution.","markdown":"An integer overflow can be triggered in SQLite\u0026#39;s `concat_ws()` function in versions prior to 3.44.4 and 3.45.0 through 3.49.0. The resulting, truncated integer is then used to allocate a buffer. When SQLite then writes the resulting string to the buffer, it uses the original, untruncated size and thus a wild Heap Buffer overflow of size ~4GB can be triggered. This can result in arbitrary code execution."},"fullDescription":{"text":"An integer overflow can be triggered in SQLite\u0026#39;s `concat_ws()` function in versions prior to 3.44.4 and 3.45.0 through 3.49.0. The resulting, truncated integer is then used to allocate a buffer. When SQLite then writes the resulting string to the buffer, it uses the original, untruncated size and thus a wild Heap Buffer overflow of size ~4GB can be triggered. This can result in arbitrary code execution."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20253277","id":"CVE-2025-3277 (containers)","description":"An integer overflow can be triggered in SQLite\u0026#39;s `concat_ws()` function in versions prior to 3.44.4 and 3.45.0 through 3.49.0. The resulting, truncated integer is then used to allocate a buffer. When SQLite then writes the resulting string to the buffer, it uses the original, untruncated size and thus a wild Heap Buffer overflow of size ~4GB can be triggered. This can result in arbitrary code execution.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-32988 (containers)","name":"Cve202532988","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A flaw was found in GnuTLS. A double-free vulnerability exists in GnuTLS due to incorrect ownership handling in the export logic of Subject Alternative Name (SAN) entries containing an otherName. If the type-id OID is invalid or malformed, GnuTLS will call asn1_delete_structure() on an ASN.1 node it does not own, leading to a double-free condition when the parent function or caller later attempts to free the same structure.\n\nThis vulnerability can be triggered using only public GnuTLS APIs and may result in denial of service or memory corruption, depending on allocator behavior.","markdown":"A flaw was found in GnuTLS. A double-free vulnerability exists in GnuTLS due to incorrect ownership handling in the export logic of Subject Alternative Name (SAN) entries containing an otherName. If the type-id OID is invalid or malformed, GnuTLS will call asn1_delete_structure() on an ASN.1 node it does not own, leading to a double-free condition when the parent function or caller later attempts to free the same structure.\n\nThis vulnerability can be triggered using only public GnuTLS APIs and may result in denial of service or memory corruption, depending on allocator behavior."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A flaw was found in GnuTLS. A double-free vulnerability exists in GnuTLS due to incorrect ownership handling in the export logic of Subject Alternative Name (SAN) entries containing an otherName. If the type-id OID is invalid or malformed, GnuTLS will call asn1_delete_structure() on an ASN.1 node it does not own, leading to a double-free condition when the parent function or caller later attempts to free the same structure.\n\nThis vulnerability can be triggered using only public GnuTLS APIs and may result in denial of service or memory corruption, depending on allocator behavior."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202532988","id":"CVE-2025-32988 (containers)","description":"A flaw was found in GnuTLS. A double-free vulnerability exists in GnuTLS due to incorrect ownership handling in the export logic of Subject Alternative Name (SAN) entries containing an otherName. If the type-id OID is invalid or malformed, GnuTLS will call asn1_delete_structure() on an ASN.1 node it does not own, leading to a double-free condition when the parent function or caller later attempts to free the same structure.\n\nThis vulnerability can be triggered using only public GnuTLS APIs and may result in denial of service or memory corruption, depending on allocator behavior.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-1178 (containers)","name":"Cve20251178","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A vulnerability has been identified in GNU Binutils, specifically in the function \u0026#34;bfd_putl64\u0026#34; within the file \u0026#34;libbfd.c\u0026#34; of the component. This vulnerability leads to memory corruption. The attack can be executed remotely, but it requires a high level of complexity and exploitation appears to be difficult. The vulnerability has been publicly disclosed and may be exploited. It is recommended to apply the patch to address this issue.","markdown":"A vulnerability has been identified in GNU Binutils, specifically in the function \u0026#34;bfd_putl64\u0026#34; within the file \u0026#34;libbfd.c\u0026#34; of the component. This vulnerability leads to memory corruption. The attack can be executed remotely, but it requires a high level of complexity and exploitation appears to be difficult. The vulnerability has been publicly disclosed and may be exploited. It is recommended to apply the patch to address this issue."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A vulnerability has been identified in GNU Binutils, specifically in the function \u0026#34;bfd_putl64\u0026#34; within the file \u0026#34;libbfd.c\u0026#34; of the component. This vulnerability leads to memory corruption. The attack can be executed remotely, but it requires a high level of complexity and exploitation appears to be difficult. The vulnerability has been publicly disclosed and may be exploited. It is recommended to apply the patch to address this issue."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20251178","id":"CVE-2025-1178 (containers)","description":"A vulnerability has been identified in GNU Binutils, specifically in the function \u0026#34;bfd_putl64\u0026#34; within the file \u0026#34;libbfd.c\u0026#34; of the component. This vulnerability leads to memory corruption. The attack can be executed remotely, but it requires a high level of complexity and exploitation appears to be difficult. The vulnerability has been publicly disclosed and may be exploited. It is recommended to apply the patch to address this issue.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2024-9143 (containers)","name":"Cve20249143","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The vulnerability involves the use of low-level GF(2^m) elliptic curve APIs with untrusted explicit values for the field polynomial, which can result in out-of-bounds memory reads or writes. The affected APIs include \u0026#34;EC_GROUP_new_curve_GF2m()\u0026#34;, \u0026#34;EC_GROUP_new_from_params()\u0026#34;, and various \u0026#34;BN_GF2m_*()\u0026#34; functions.\n\nWhile out-of-bounds memory writes could lead to application crashes or even potential remote code execution, the likelihood of a vulnerable application is considered low. This is because protocols that employ Elliptic Curve Cryptography generally use \u0026#34;named curves,\u0026#34; or if explicit curve parameters are supported, they rely on X9.62 encoding, which does not permit problematic input values. X9.62 encoding is also used for ECC keys in X.509 certificates, making the occurrence of problematic inputs in that context unlikely. Applications utilizing \u0026#34;exotic\u0026#34; explicit binary (GF(2^m)) curve parameters that allow the representation of invalid field polynomials with a zero constant term may encounter abrupt termination due to array bounds violations. While remote code execution cannot be easily ruled out, it remains a less likely scenario.\n\nThe vulnerability affects openssl versions 1.0.2-x prior to 1.0.2zl, 1.1.x prior to 1.1.1zb, 3.0.x prior to 3.0.16, 3.1.x prior to 3.1.8, 3.2.x prior to 3.2.4, 3.3.x prior to 3.3.3, and 3.4.x prior to 3.4.0.","markdown":"The vulnerability involves the use of low-level GF(2^m) elliptic curve APIs with untrusted explicit values for the field polynomial, which can result in out-of-bounds memory reads or writes. The affected APIs include \u0026#34;EC_GROUP_new_curve_GF2m()\u0026#34;, \u0026#34;EC_GROUP_new_from_params()\u0026#34;, and various \u0026#34;BN_GF2m_*()\u0026#34; functions.\n\nWhile out-of-bounds memory writes could lead to application crashes or even potential remote code execution, the likelihood of a vulnerable application is considered low. This is because protocols that employ Elliptic Curve Cryptography generally use \u0026#34;named curves,\u0026#34; or if explicit curve parameters are supported, they rely on X9.62 encoding, which does not permit problematic input values. X9.62 encoding is also used for ECC keys in X.509 certificates, making the occurrence of problematic inputs in that context unlikely. Applications utilizing \u0026#34;exotic\u0026#34; explicit binary (GF(2^m)) curve parameters that allow the representation of invalid field polynomials with a zero constant term may encounter abrupt termination due to array bounds violations. While remote code execution cannot be easily ruled out, it remains a less likely scenario.\n\nThe vulnerability affects openssl versions 1.0.2-x prior to 1.0.2zl, 1.1.x prior to 1.1.1zb, 3.0.x prior to 3.0.16, 3.1.x prior to 3.1.8, 3.2.x prior to 3.2.4, 3.3.x prior to 3.3.3, and 3.4.x prior to 3.4.0."},"fullDescription":{"text":"The vulnerability involves the use of low-level GF(2^m) elliptic curve APIs with untrusted explicit values for the field polynomial, which can result in out-of-bounds memory reads or writes. The affected APIs include \u0026#34;EC_GROUP_new_curve_GF2m()\u0026#34;, \u0026#34;EC_GROUP_new_from_params()\u0026#34;, and various \u0026#34;BN_GF2m_*()\u0026#34; functions.\n\nWhile out-of-bounds memory writes could lead to application crashes or even potential remote code execution, the likelihood of a vulnerable application is considered low. This is because protocols that employ Elliptic Curve Cryptography generally use \u0026#34;named curves,\u0026#34; or if explicit curve parameters are supported, they rely on X9.62 encoding, which does not permit problematic input values. X9.62 encoding is also used for ECC keys in X.509 certificates, making the occurrence of problematic inputs in that context unlikely. Applications utilizing \u0026#34;exotic\u0026#34; explicit binary (GF(2^m)) curve parameters that allow the representation of invalid field polynomials with a zero constant term may encounter abrupt termination due to array bounds violations. While remote code execution cannot be easily ruled out, it remains a less likely scenario.\n\nThe vulnerability affects openssl versions 1.0.2-x prior to 1.0.2zl, 1.1.x prior to 1.1.1zb, 3.0.x prior to 3.0.16, 3.1.x prior to 3.1.8, 3.2.x prior to 3.2.4, 3.3.x prior to 3.3.3, and 3.4.x prior to 3.4.0."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20249143","id":"CVE-2024-9143 (containers)","description":"The vulnerability involves the use of low-level GF(2^m) elliptic curve APIs with untrusted explicit values for the field polynomial, which can result in out-of-bounds memory reads or writes. The affected APIs include \u0026#34;EC_GROUP_new_curve_GF2m()\u0026#34;, \u0026#34;EC_GROUP_new_from_params()\u0026#34;, and various \u0026#34;BN_GF2m_*()\u0026#34; functions.\n\nWhile out-of-bounds memory writes could lead to application crashes or even potential remote code execution, the likelihood of a vulnerable application is considered low. This is because protocols that employ Elliptic Curve Cryptography generally use \u0026#34;named curves,\u0026#34; or if explicit curve parameters are supported, they rely on X9.62 encoding, which does not permit problematic input values. X9.62 encoding is also used for ECC keys in X.509 certificates, making the occurrence of problematic inputs in that context unlikely. Applications utilizing \u0026#34;exotic\u0026#34; explicit binary (GF(2^m)) curve parameters that allow the representation of invalid field polynomials with a zero constant term may encounter abrupt termination due to array bounds violations. While remote code execution cannot be easily ruled out, it remains a less likely scenario.\n\nThe vulnerability affects openssl versions 1.0.2-x prior to 1.0.2zl, 1.1.x prior to 1.1.1zb, 3.0.x prior to 3.0.16, 3.1.x prior to 3.1.8, 3.2.x prior to 3.2.4, 3.3.x prior to 3.3.3, and 3.4.x prior to 3.4.0.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-5745 (containers)","name":"Cve20255745","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The \u0026#34;strncmp\u0026#34; implementation optimized for the Power10 processor in the GNU C Library version 2.39 and later writes to vector registers v20 to v31 without saving contents from the caller (those registers are defined as non-volatile registers by the powerpc64le ABI), resulting in overwriting of its contents and potentially altering control flow of the caller, or leaking the input strings to the function to other parts of the program.","markdown":"The \u0026#34;strncmp\u0026#34; implementation optimized for the Power10 processor in the GNU C Library version 2.39 and later writes to vector registers v20 to v31 without saving contents from the caller (those registers are defined as non-volatile registers by the powerpc64le ABI), resulting in overwriting of its contents and potentially altering control flow of the caller, or leaking the input strings to the function to other parts of the program."},"fullDescription":{"text":"The \u0026#34;strncmp\u0026#34; implementation optimized for the Power10 processor in the GNU C Library version 2.39 and later writes to vector registers v20 to v31 without saving contents from the caller (those registers are defined as non-volatile registers by the powerpc64le ABI), resulting in overwriting of its contents and potentially altering control flow of the caller, or leaking the input strings to the function to other parts of the program."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20255745","id":"CVE-2025-5745 (containers)","description":"The \u0026#34;strncmp\u0026#34; implementation optimized for the Power10 processor in the GNU C Library version 2.39 and later writes to vector registers v20 to v31 without saving contents from the caller (those registers are defined as non-volatile registers by the powerpc64le ABI), resulting in overwriting of its contents and potentially altering control flow of the caller, or leaking the input strings to the function to other parts of the program.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2024-13176 (containers)","name":"Cve202413176","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Issue summary: A timing side-channel which could potentially allow recovering the private key exists in the ECDSA signature computation in OpenSSL. Impact summary: A timing side-channel in ECDSA signature computations could allow recovering the private key by an attacker. However, measuring the timing would require either local access to the signing application or a very fast network connection with low latency. There is a timing signal of around `300` nanoseconds when the top word of the inverted ECDSA nonce value is zero. This can happen with significant probability only for some of the supported elliptic curves. In particular, the `NIST P-521` curve is affected. To be able to measure this leak, the attacker process must either be located on the same physical computer or must have a very fast network connection with low latency. For that reason, the severity of this vulnerability is low. This issue affects openssl package through 3.0.15, 3.1.0-alpha1 through 3.1.7, 3.2.0-alpha1 through 3.2.3, 3.3.0-alpha1 through 3.3.2, and 3.4.0-alpha1 through 3.4.0. Note: This vulnerability also fixed in 1.0.2zl , and 1.1.1zb only for premium support customers.","markdown":"Issue summary: A timing side-channel which could potentially allow recovering the private key exists in the ECDSA signature computation in OpenSSL. Impact summary: A timing side-channel in ECDSA signature computations could allow recovering the private key by an attacker. However, measuring the timing would require either local access to the signing application or a very fast network connection with low latency. There is a timing signal of around `300` nanoseconds when the top word of the inverted ECDSA nonce value is zero. This can happen with significant probability only for some of the supported elliptic curves. In particular, the `NIST P-521` curve is affected. To be able to measure this leak, the attacker process must either be located on the same physical computer or must have a very fast network connection with low latency. For that reason, the severity of this vulnerability is low. This issue affects openssl package through 3.0.15, 3.1.0-alpha1 through 3.1.7, 3.2.0-alpha1 through 3.2.3, 3.3.0-alpha1 through 3.3.2, and 3.4.0-alpha1 through 3.4.0. Note: This vulnerability also fixed in 1.0.2zl , and 1.1.1zb only for premium support customers."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Issue summary: A timing side-channel which could potentially allow recovering the private key exists in the ECDSA signature computation in OpenSSL. Impact summary: A timing side-channel in ECDSA signature computations could allow recovering the private key by an attacker. However, measuring the timing would require either local access to the signing application or a very fast network connection with low latency. There is a timing signal of around `300` nanoseconds when the top word of the inverted ECDSA nonce value is zero. This can happen with significant probability only for some of the supported elliptic curves. In particular, the `NIST P-521` curve is affected. To be able to measure this leak, the attacker process must either be located on the same physical computer or must have a very fast network connection with low latency. For that reason, the severity of this vulnerability is low. This issue affects openssl package through 3.0.15, 3.1.0-alpha1 through 3.1.7, 3.2.0-alpha1 through 3.2.3, 3.3.0-alpha1 through 3.3.2, and 3.4.0-alpha1 through 3.4.0. Note: This vulnerability also fixed in 1.0.2zl , and 1.1.1zb only for premium support customers."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202413176","id":"CVE-2024-13176 (containers)","description":"Issue summary: A timing side-channel which could potentially allow recovering the private key exists in the ECDSA signature computation in OpenSSL. Impact summary: A timing side-channel in ECDSA signature computations could allow recovering the private key by an attacker. However, measuring the timing would require either local access to the signing application or a very fast network connection with low latency. There is a timing signal of around `300` nanoseconds when the top word of the inverted ECDSA nonce value is zero. This can happen with significant probability only for some of the supported elliptic curves. In particular, the `NIST P-521` curve is affected. To be able to measure this leak, the attacker process must either be located on the same physical computer or must have a very fast network connection with low latency. For that reason, the severity of this vulnerability is low. This issue affects openssl package through 3.0.15, 3.1.0-alpha1 through 3.1.7, 3.2.0-alpha1 through 3.2.3, 3.3.0-alpha1 through 3.3.2, and 3.4.0-alpha1 through 3.4.0. Note: This vulnerability also fixed in 1.0.2zl , and 1.1.1zb only for premium support customers.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-4598 (containers)","name":"Cve20254598","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A vulnerability was found in systemd-coredump. This flaw allows an attacker to force a SUID process to crash and replace it with a non-SUID binary to access the original\u0026#39;s privileged process coredump, allowing the attacker to read sensitive data, such as /etc/shadow content, loaded by the original process.\n\nA SUID binary or process has a special type of permission, which allows the process to run with the file owner\u0026#39;s permissions, regardless of the user executing the binary. This allows the process to access more restricted data than unprivileged users or processes would be able to. An attacker can leverage this flaw by forcing a SUID process to crash and force the Linux kernel to recycle the process PID before systemd-coredump can analyze the \u0026#34;/proc/pid/auxv\u0026#34; file. If the attacker wins the race condition, they gain access to the original\u0026#39;s SUID process coredump file. They can read sensitive content loaded into memory by the original binary, affecting data confidentiality. This issue affects systemd versions prior to prior to v256.14, v257-x prior to v257.6 and systemd-stable versions prior to v252.37, v253.x prior to 253.32, v254.x prior to v254.25, v255.x prior to v255.19 and v256.x and later.","markdown":"A vulnerability was found in systemd-coredump. This flaw allows an attacker to force a SUID process to crash and replace it with a non-SUID binary to access the original\u0026#39;s privileged process coredump, allowing the attacker to read sensitive data, such as /etc/shadow content, loaded by the original process.\n\nA SUID binary or process has a special type of permission, which allows the process to run with the file owner\u0026#39;s permissions, regardless of the user executing the binary. This allows the process to access more restricted data than unprivileged users or processes would be able to. An attacker can leverage this flaw by forcing a SUID process to crash and force the Linux kernel to recycle the process PID before systemd-coredump can analyze the \u0026#34;/proc/pid/auxv\u0026#34; file. If the attacker wins the race condition, they gain access to the original\u0026#39;s SUID process coredump file. They can read sensitive content loaded into memory by the original binary, affecting data confidentiality. This issue affects systemd versions prior to prior to v256.14, v257-x prior to v257.6 and systemd-stable versions prior to v252.37, v253.x prior to 253.32, v254.x prior to v254.25, v255.x prior to v255.19 and v256.x and later."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A vulnerability was found in systemd-coredump. This flaw allows an attacker to force a SUID process to crash and replace it with a non-SUID binary to access the original\u0026#39;s privileged process coredump, allowing the attacker to read sensitive data, such as /etc/shadow content, loaded by the original process.\n\nA SUID binary or process has a special type of permission, which allows the process to run with the file owner\u0026#39;s permissions, regardless of the user executing the binary. This allows the process to access more restricted data than unprivileged users or processes would be able to. An attacker can leverage this flaw by forcing a SUID process to crash and force the Linux kernel to recycle the process PID before systemd-coredump can analyze the \u0026#34;/proc/pid/auxv\u0026#34; file. If the attacker wins the race condition, they gain access to the original\u0026#39;s SUID process coredump file. They can read sensitive content loaded into memory by the original binary, affecting data confidentiality. This issue affects systemd versions prior to prior to v256.14, v257-x prior to v257.6 and systemd-stable versions prior to v252.37, v253.x prior to 253.32, v254.x prior to v254.25, v255.x prior to v255.19 and v256.x and later."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20254598","id":"CVE-2025-4598 (containers)","description":"A vulnerability was found in systemd-coredump. This flaw allows an attacker to force a SUID process to crash and replace it with a non-SUID binary to access the original\u0026#39;s privileged process coredump, allowing the attacker to read sensitive data, such as /etc/shadow content, loaded by the original process.\n\nA SUID binary or process has a special type of permission, which allows the process to run with the file owner\u0026#39;s permissions, regardless of the user executing the binary. This allows the process to access more restricted data than unprivileged users or processes would be able to. An attacker can leverage this flaw by forcing a SUID process to crash and force the Linux kernel to recycle the process PID before systemd-coredump can analyze the \u0026#34;/proc/pid/auxv\u0026#34; file. If the attacker wins the race condition, they gain access to the original\u0026#39;s SUID process coredump file. They can read sensitive content loaded into memory by the original binary, affecting data confidentiality. This issue affects systemd versions prior to prior to v256.14, v257-x prior to v257.6 and systemd-stable versions prior to v252.37, v253.x prior to 253.32, v254.x prior to v254.25, v255.x prior to v255.19 and v256.x and later.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2024-12243 (containers)","name":"Cve202412243","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A flaw was found in GnuTLS, which relies on libtasn1 for ASN.1 data processing. Due to an inefficient algorithm in libtasn1, decoding certain DER-encoded certificate data can take excessive time, leading to increased resource consumption. This flaw allows a remote attacker to send a specially crafted certificate, causing GnuTLS to become unresponsive or slow, resulting in a denial-of-service condition.","markdown":"A flaw was found in GnuTLS, which relies on libtasn1 for ASN.1 data processing. Due to an inefficient algorithm in libtasn1, decoding certain DER-encoded certificate data can take excessive time, leading to increased resource consumption. This flaw allows a remote attacker to send a specially crafted certificate, causing GnuTLS to become unresponsive or slow, resulting in a denial-of-service condition."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A flaw was found in GnuTLS, which relies on libtasn1 for ASN.1 data processing. Due to an inefficient algorithm in libtasn1, decoding certain DER-encoded certificate data can take excessive time, leading to increased resource consumption. This flaw allows a remote attacker to send a specially crafted certificate, causing GnuTLS to become unresponsive or slow, resulting in a denial-of-service condition."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202412243","id":"CVE-2024-12243 (containers)","description":"A flaw was found in GnuTLS, which relies on libtasn1 for ASN.1 data processing. Due to an inefficient algorithm in libtasn1, decoding certain DER-encoded certificate data can take excessive time, leading to increased resource consumption. This flaw allows a remote attacker to send a specially crafted certificate, causing GnuTLS to become unresponsive or slow, resulting in a denial-of-service condition.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-0840 (containers)","name":"Cve20250840","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A vulnerability, which was classified as problematic, was found in GNU Binutils versions prior to 2.44. This affects the function \u0026#34;disassemble_bytes\u0026#34; of the file \u0026#34;binutils/objdump.c\u0026#34;. The manipulation of the argument buf leads to a stack-based buffer overflow. It is possible to initiate the attack remotely. The complexity of an attack is rather high. The exploitability is said to be difficult. The exploit has been disclosed to the public and may be used.","markdown":"A vulnerability, which was classified as problematic, was found in GNU Binutils versions prior to 2.44. This affects the function \u0026#34;disassemble_bytes\u0026#34; of the file \u0026#34;binutils/objdump.c\u0026#34;. The manipulation of the argument buf leads to a stack-based buffer overflow. It is possible to initiate the attack remotely. The complexity of an attack is rather high. The exploitability is said to be difficult. The exploit has been disclosed to the public and may be used."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A vulnerability, which was classified as problematic, was found in GNU Binutils versions prior to 2.44. This affects the function \u0026#34;disassemble_bytes\u0026#34; of the file \u0026#34;binutils/objdump.c\u0026#34;. The manipulation of the argument buf leads to a stack-based buffer overflow. It is possible to initiate the attack remotely. The complexity of an attack is rather high. The exploitability is said to be difficult. The exploit has been disclosed to the public and may be used."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20250840","id":"CVE-2025-0840 (containers)","description":"A vulnerability, which was classified as problematic, was found in GNU Binutils versions prior to 2.44. This affects the function \u0026#34;disassemble_bytes\u0026#34; of the file \u0026#34;binutils/objdump.c\u0026#34;. The manipulation of the argument buf leads to a stack-based buffer overflow. It is possible to initiate the attack remotely. The complexity of an attack is rather high. The exploitability is said to be difficult. The exploit has been disclosed to the public and may be used.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-40909 (containers)","name":"Cve202540909","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Perl threads have a working directory race condition where file operations may target unintended paths.\n\nIf a directory handle is open at thread creation, the process-wide current working directory is temporarily changed in order to clone that handle for the new thread, which is visible from any third (or more) thread already running. \n\nThis may lead to unintended operations such as loading code or accessing files from unexpected locations, which a local attacker may be able to exploit.\n\nThe bug was introduced in commit 11a11ecf4bea72b17d250cfb43c897be1341861e and released in Perl version 5.13.6","markdown":"Perl threads have a working directory race condition where file operations may target unintended paths.\n\nIf a directory handle is open at thread creation, the process-wide current working directory is temporarily changed in order to clone that handle for the new thread, which is visible from any third (or more) thread already running. \n\nThis may lead to unintended operations such as loading code or accessing files from unexpected locations, which a local attacker may be able to exploit.\n\nThe bug was introduced in commit 11a11ecf4bea72b17d250cfb43c897be1341861e and released in Perl version 5.13.6"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Perl threads have a working directory race condition where file operations may target unintended paths.\n\nIf a directory handle is open at thread creation, the process-wide current working directory is temporarily changed in order to clone that handle for the new thread, which is visible from any third (or more) thread already running. \n\nThis may lead to unintended operations such as loading code or accessing files from unexpected locations, which a local attacker may be able to exploit.\n\nThe bug was introduced in commit 11a11ecf4bea72b17d250cfb43c897be1341861e and released in Perl version 5.13.6"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202540909","id":"CVE-2025-40909 (containers)","description":"Perl threads have a working directory race condition where file operations may target unintended paths.\n\nIf a directory handle is open at thread creation, the process-wide current working directory is temporarily changed in order to clone that handle for the new thread, which is visible from any third (or more) thread already running. \n\nThis may lead to unintended operations such as loading code or accessing files from unexpected locations, which a local attacker may be able to exploit.\n\nThe bug was introduced in commit 11a11ecf4bea72b17d250cfb43c897be1341861e and released in Perl version 5.13.6","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-32989 (containers)","name":"Cve202532989","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A heap-buffer-overread vulnerability was found in GnuTLS in how it handles the Certificate Transparency (CT) Signed Certificate Timestamp (SCT) extension during X.509 certificate parsing. This flaw allows a malicious user to create a certificate containing a malformed SCT extension (OID 1.3.6.1.4.1.11129.2.4.2) that contains sensitive data. This issue leads to the exposure of confidential information when GnuTLS verifies certificates from certain websites when the certificate (SCT) is not checked correctly.","markdown":"A heap-buffer-overread vulnerability was found in GnuTLS in how it handles the Certificate Transparency (CT) Signed Certificate Timestamp (SCT) extension during X.509 certificate parsing. This flaw allows a malicious user to create a certificate containing a malformed SCT extension (OID 1.3.6.1.4.1.11129.2.4.2) that contains sensitive data. This issue leads to the exposure of confidential information when GnuTLS verifies certificates from certain websites when the certificate (SCT) is not checked correctly."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A heap-buffer-overread vulnerability was found in GnuTLS in how it handles the Certificate Transparency (CT) Signed Certificate Timestamp (SCT) extension during X.509 certificate parsing. This flaw allows a malicious user to create a certificate containing a malformed SCT extension (OID 1.3.6.1.4.1.11129.2.4.2) that contains sensitive data. This issue leads to the exposure of confidential information when GnuTLS verifies certificates from certain websites when the certificate (SCT) is not checked correctly."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202532989","id":"CVE-2025-32989 (containers)","description":"A heap-buffer-overread vulnerability was found in GnuTLS in how it handles the Certificate Transparency (CT) Signed Certificate Timestamp (SCT) extension during X.509 certificate parsing. This flaw allows a malicious user to create a certificate containing a malformed SCT extension (OID 1.3.6.1.4.1.11129.2.4.2) that contains sensitive data. This issue leads to the exposure of confidential information when GnuTLS verifies certificates from certain websites when the certificate (SCT) is not checked correctly.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-6395 (containers)","name":"Cve20256395","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A NULL pointer dereference flaw was found in the GnuTLS software in _gnutls_figure_common_ciphersuite().","markdown":"A NULL pointer dereference flaw was found in the GnuTLS software in _gnutls_figure_common_ciphersuite()."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A NULL pointer dereference flaw was found in the GnuTLS software in _gnutls_figure_common_ciphersuite()."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20256395","id":"CVE-2025-6395 (containers)","description":"A NULL pointer dereference flaw was found in the GnuTLS software in _gnutls_figure_common_ciphersuite().","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-1390 (containers)","name":"Cve20251390","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The PAM module pam_cap.so of libcap configuration supports group names starting with “@”, during actual parsing, configurations not starting with “@” are incorrectly recognized as group names. This may result in nonintended users being granted an inherited capability set, potentially leading to security risks. Attackers can exploit this vulnerability to achieve local privilege escalation on systems where /etc/security/capability.conf is used to configure user inherited privileges by constructing specific usernames.","markdown":"The PAM module pam_cap.so of libcap configuration supports group names starting with “@”, during actual parsing, configurations not starting with “@” are incorrectly recognized as group names. This may result in nonintended users being granted an inherited capability set, potentially leading to security risks. Attackers can exploit this vulnerability to achieve local privilege escalation on systems where /etc/security/capability.conf is used to configure user inherited privileges by constructing specific usernames."},"fullDescription":{"text":"The PAM module pam_cap.so of libcap configuration supports group names starting with “@”, during actual parsing, configurations not starting with “@” are incorrectly recognized as group names. This may result in nonintended users being granted an inherited capability set, potentially leading to security risks. Attackers can exploit this vulnerability to achieve local privilege escalation on systems where /etc/security/capability.conf is used to configure user inherited privileges by constructing specific usernames."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve20251390","id":"CVE-2025-1390 (containers)","description":"The PAM module pam_cap.so of libcap configuration supports group names starting with “@”, during actual parsing, configurations not starting with “@” are incorrectly recognized as group names. This may result in nonintended users being granted an inherited capability set, potentially leading to security risks. Attackers can exploit this vulnerability to achieve local privilege escalation on systems where /etc/security/capability.conf is used to configure user inherited privileges by constructing specific usernames.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-29088 (containers)","name":"Cve202529088","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"In SQLite version through  3.44.3 and in version 3.45.0  through 3.49.0, certain argument values to \u0026#34;sqlite3_db_config\u0026#34; (in the C-language API) can cause a Denial Of Service (application crash). An \u0026#34;sz*nBig\u0026#34; multiplication is not cast to a 64-bit integer, and consequently some memory allocations may be incorrect.","markdown":"In SQLite version through  3.44.3 and in version 3.45.0  through 3.49.0, certain argument values to \u0026#34;sqlite3_db_config\u0026#34; (in the C-language API) can cause a Denial Of Service (application crash). An \u0026#34;sz*nBig\u0026#34; multiplication is not cast to a 64-bit integer, and consequently some memory allocations may be incorrect."},"fullDescription":{"text":"In SQLite version through  3.44.3 and in version 3.45.0  through 3.49.0, certain argument values to \u0026#34;sqlite3_db_config\u0026#34; (in the C-language API) can cause a Denial Of Service (application crash). An \u0026#34;sz*nBig\u0026#34; multiplication is not cast to a 64-bit integer, and consequently some memory allocations may be incorrect."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202529088","id":"CVE-2025-29088 (containers)","description":"In SQLite version through  3.44.3 and in version 3.45.0  through 3.49.0, certain argument values to \u0026#34;sqlite3_db_config\u0026#34; (in the C-language API) can cause a Denial Of Service (application crash). An \u0026#34;sz*nBig\u0026#34; multiplication is not cast to a 64-bit integer, and consequently some memory allocations may be incorrect.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-32990 (containers)","name":"Cve202532990","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A heap-buffer-overflow (off-by-one) flaw was found in the GnuTLS software in the template parsing logic within the certtool utility. When it reads certain settings from a template file, it allows an attacker to cause an out-of-bounds (OOB) NULL pointer write, resulting in memory corruption and a denial-of-service (DoS) that could potentially crash the system.","markdown":"A heap-buffer-overflow (off-by-one) flaw was found in the GnuTLS software in the template parsing logic within the certtool utility. When it reads certain settings from a template file, it allows an attacker to cause an out-of-bounds (OOB) NULL pointer write, resulting in memory corruption and a denial-of-service (DoS) that could potentially crash the system."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A heap-buffer-overflow (off-by-one) flaw was found in the GnuTLS software in the template parsing logic within the certtool utility. When it reads certain settings from a template file, it allows an attacker to cause an out-of-bounds (OOB) NULL pointer write, resulting in memory corruption and a denial-of-service (DoS) that could potentially crash the system."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202532990","id":"CVE-2025-32990 (containers)","description":"A heap-buffer-overflow (off-by-one) flaw was found in the GnuTLS software in the template parsing logic within the certtool utility. When it reads certain settings from a template file, it allows an attacker to cause an out-of-bounds (OOB) NULL pointer write, resulting in memory corruption and a denial-of-service (DoS) that could potentially crash the system.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2020-26259 (sca)","name":"Cve202026259","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"XStream is a Java library to serialize objects to XML and back again. In XStream before version 1.4.15, is vulnerable to an Arbitrary File Deletion on the local host when unmarshalling. The vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to delete arbitrary known files on the host as long as the executing process has sufficient rights only by manipulating the processed input stream. If you rely on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist of the Security Framework, you will have to use at least version 1.4.15. The reported vulnerability does not exist running Java 15 or higher. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s Security Framework with a whitelist! Anyone relying on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist can immediately switch to a whilelist for the allowed types to avoid the vulnerability. Users of XStream 1.4.14 or below who still want to use XStream default blacklist can use a workaround described in more detailed in the referenced advisories.","markdown":"XStream is a Java library to serialize objects to XML and back again. In XStream before version 1.4.15, is vulnerable to an Arbitrary File Deletion on the local host when unmarshalling. The vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to delete arbitrary known files on the host as long as the executing process has sufficient rights only by manipulating the processed input stream. If you rely on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist of the Security Framework, you will have to use at least version 1.4.15. The reported vulnerability does not exist running Java 15 or higher. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s Security Framework with a whitelist! Anyone relying on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist can immediately switch to a whilelist for the allowed types to avoid the vulnerability. Users of XStream 1.4.14 or below who still want to use XStream default blacklist can use a workaround described in more detailed in the referenced advisories."},"fullDescription":{"text":"XStream is a Java library to serialize objects to XML and back again. In XStream before version 1.4.15, is vulnerable to an Arbitrary File Deletion on the local host when unmarshalling. The vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to delete arbitrary known files on the host as long as the executing process has sufficient rights only by manipulating the processed input stream. If you rely on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist of the Security Framework, you will have to use at least version 1.4.15. The reported vulnerability does not exist running Java 15 or higher. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s Security Framework with a whitelist! Anyone relying on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist can immediately switch to a whilelist for the allowed types to avoid the vulnerability. Users of XStream 1.4.14 or below who still want to use XStream default blacklist can use a workaround described in more detailed in the referenced advisories."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202026259","id":"CVE-2020-26259 (sca)","description":"XStream is a Java library to serialize objects to XML and back again. In XStream before version 1.4.15, is vulnerable to an Arbitrary File Deletion on the local host when unmarshalling. The vulnerability may allow a remote attacker to delete arbitrary known files on the host as long as the executing process has sufficient rights only by manipulating the processed input stream. If you rely on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist of the Security Framework, you will have to use at least version 1.4.15. The reported vulnerability does not exist running Java 15 or higher. No user is affected, who followed the recommendation to setup XStream\u0026#39;s Security Framework with a whitelist! Anyone relying on XStream\u0026#39;s default blacklist can immediately switch to a whilelist for the allowed types to avoid the vulnerability. Users of XStream 1.4.14 or below who still want to use XStream default blacklist can use a workaround described in more detailed in the referenced advisories.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"Dangerous File Size Upload - 5783575033343291143 (sast)","name":"Dangerous File Size Upload","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The uploaded file text in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/xxe/Ping.java at line 46 is stored in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/xxe/Ping.java at line 53 without validating the size of the file being saved.","markdown":"The uploaded file text in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/xxe/Ping.java at line 46 is stored in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/xxe/Ping.java at line 53 without validating the size of the file being saved."},"fullDescription":{"text":"The uploaded file text in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/xxe/Ping.java at line 46 is stored in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/xxe/Ping.java at line 53 without validating the size of the file being saved."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Dangerous File Size Upload","id":"Dangerous File Size Upload - 5783575033343291143 (sast)","description":"The uploaded file text in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/xxe/Ping.java at line 46 is stored in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/xxe/Ping.java at line 53 without validating the size of the file being saved.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Unchecked Input For Loop Condition - 2735238463262621248 (sast)","name":"Unchecked Input For Loop Condition","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Method Lambda at line 21094 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/resources/webgoat/static/js/libs/ace.js obtains user input from data - the range of this value is not validated, and is eventually used in a loop condition in Lambda at line 21098 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/resources/webgoat/static/js/libs/ace.js, allowing attackers to provide a very high number of iterations.\n\n","markdown":"Method Lambda at line 21094 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/resources/webgoat/static/js/libs/ace.js obtains user input from data - the range of this value is not validated, and is eventually used in a loop condition in Lambda at line 21098 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/resources/webgoat/static/js/libs/ace.js, allowing attackers to provide a very high number of iterations.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Method Lambda at line 21094 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/resources/webgoat/static/js/libs/ace.js obtains user input from data - the range of this value is not validated, and is eventually used in a loop condition in Lambda at line 21098 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/resources/webgoat/static/js/libs/ace.js, allowing attackers to provide a very high number of iterations.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Unchecked Input For Loop Condition","id":"Unchecked Input For Loop Condition - 2735238463262621248 (sast)","description":"Method Lambda at line 21094 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/resources/webgoat/static/js/libs/ace.js obtains user input from data - the range of this value is not validated, and is eventually used in a loop condition in Lambda at line 21098 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/resources/webgoat/static/js/libs/ace.js, allowing attackers to provide a very high number of iterations.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Stored Absolute Path Traversal - 16226857271836006613 (sast)","name":"Stored Absolute Path Traversal","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Method processZipUpload at line 75 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/pathtraversal/ProfileZipSlip.java gets dynamic data from the toFile element. This element’s value then flows through the code and is eventually used in a file path for local disk access in processZipUpload at line 75 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/pathtraversal/ProfileZipSlip.java. This may cause a Path Traversal vulnerability.\n\n","markdown":"Method processZipUpload at line 75 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/pathtraversal/ProfileZipSlip.java gets dynamic data from the toFile element. This element’s value then flows through the code and is eventually used in a file path for local disk access in processZipUpload at line 75 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/pathtraversal/ProfileZipSlip.java. This may cause a Path Traversal vulnerability.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Method processZipUpload at line 75 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/pathtraversal/ProfileZipSlip.java gets dynamic data from the toFile element. This element’s value then flows through the code and is eventually used in a file path for local disk access in processZipUpload at line 75 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/pathtraversal/ProfileZipSlip.java. This may cause a Path Traversal vulnerability.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Stored Absolute Path Traversal","id":"Stored Absolute Path Traversal - 16226857271836006613 (sast)","description":"Method processZipUpload at line 75 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/pathtraversal/ProfileZipSlip.java gets dynamic data from the toFile element. This element’s value then flows through the code and is eventually used in a file path for local disk access in processZipUpload at line 75 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/pathtraversal/ProfileZipSlip.java. This may cause a Path Traversal vulnerability.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Cxf0b588a3-5c6f (sca)","name":"Cxf0b588a35c6f","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The package `jQuery` before 1.12.0, between 1.12.2 and 2.1.4 and between 2.2.2 and 2.2.4 is vulnerable to `XSS`. The function `jQuery.parseHTML()` in the file `src/core/parseHTML.js` doesn\u0026#39;t stop scripts or inline event handlers from being executed immediately, which could result in XSS as the attacker could embed malicious scripts in the HTML (img nodes with embedded src url\u0026#39;s which are pre-loaded when the page is requested) which would get executed immediately in the victim\u0026#39;s browser even without user\u0026#39;s intervention.","markdown":"The package `jQuery` before 1.12.0, between 1.12.2 and 2.1.4 and between 2.2.2 and 2.2.4 is vulnerable to `XSS`. The function `jQuery.parseHTML()` in the file `src/core/parseHTML.js` doesn\u0026#39;t stop scripts or inline event handlers from being executed immediately, which could result in XSS as the attacker could embed malicious scripts in the HTML (img nodes with embedded src url\u0026#39;s which are pre-loaded when the page is requested) which would get executed immediately in the victim\u0026#39;s browser even without user\u0026#39;s intervention."},"fullDescription":{"text":"The package `jQuery` before 1.12.0, between 1.12.2 and 2.1.4 and between 2.2.2 and 2.2.4 is vulnerable to `XSS`. The function `jQuery.parseHTML()` in the file `src/core/parseHTML.js` doesn\u0026#39;t stop scripts or inline event handlers from being executed immediately, which could result in XSS as the attacker could embed malicious scripts in the HTML (img nodes with embedded src url\u0026#39;s which are pre-loaded when the page is requested) which would get executed immediately in the victim\u0026#39;s browser even without user\u0026#39;s intervention."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cxf0b588a35c6f","id":"Cxf0b588a3-5c6f (sca)","description":"The package `jQuery` before 1.12.0, between 1.12.2 and 2.1.4 and between 2.2.2 and 2.2.4 is vulnerable to `XSS`. The function `jQuery.parseHTML()` in the file `src/core/parseHTML.js` doesn\u0026#39;t stop scripts or inline event handlers from being executed immediately, which could result in XSS as the attacker could embed malicious scripts in the HTML (img nodes with embedded src url\u0026#39;s which are pre-loaded when the page is requested) which would get executed immediately in the victim\u0026#39;s browser even without user\u0026#39;s intervention.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-49125 (sca)","name":"Cve202549125","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Authentication Bypass Using an Alternate Path or Channel vulnerability in Apache Tomcat. When using `PreResources` or `PostResources` mounted other than at the root of the web application, it was possible to access those resources via an unexpected path. That path was likely not to be protected by the same security constraints as the expected path, allowing those security constraints to be bypassed.\nThis issue affects Apache Tomcat versions 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.105, 10.1.0-M1 through 10.1.41, and 11.0.0-M1 through 11.0.7.","markdown":"Authentication Bypass Using an Alternate Path or Channel vulnerability in Apache Tomcat. When using `PreResources` or `PostResources` mounted other than at the root of the web application, it was possible to access those resources via an unexpected path. That path was likely not to be protected by the same security constraints as the expected path, allowing those security constraints to be bypassed.\nThis issue affects Apache Tomcat versions 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.105, 10.1.0-M1 through 10.1.41, and 11.0.0-M1 through 11.0.7."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Authentication Bypass Using an Alternate Path or Channel vulnerability in Apache Tomcat. When using `PreResources` or `PostResources` mounted other than at the root of the web application, it was possible to access those resources via an unexpected path. That path was likely not to be protected by the same security constraints as the expected path, allowing those security constraints to be bypassed.\nThis issue affects Apache Tomcat versions 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.105, 10.1.0-M1 through 10.1.41, and 11.0.0-M1 through 11.0.7."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202549125","id":"CVE-2025-49125 (sca)","description":"Authentication Bypass Using an Alternate Path or Channel vulnerability in Apache Tomcat. When using `PreResources` or `PostResources` mounted other than at the root of the web application, it was possible to access those resources via an unexpected path. That path was likely not to be protected by the same security constraints as the expected path, allowing those security constraints to be bypassed.\nThis issue affects Apache Tomcat versions 9.0.0.M1 through 9.0.105, 10.1.0-M1 through 10.1.41, and 11.0.0-M1 through 11.0.7.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"Excessive Data Exposure - 888037238381873240 (sast)","name":"Excessive Data Exposure","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The data in PASSWORD_SALT_ADMIN at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java in line 88 may be sensitive, and it is exposed by an API at PASSWORD_SALT_ADMIN in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java at line 88.\n\n","markdown":"The data in PASSWORD_SALT_ADMIN at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java in line 88 may be sensitive, and it is exposed by an API at PASSWORD_SALT_ADMIN in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java at line 88.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The data in PASSWORD_SALT_ADMIN at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java in line 88 may be sensitive, and it is exposed by an API at PASSWORD_SALT_ADMIN in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java at line 88.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Excessive Data Exposure","id":"Excessive Data Exposure - 888037238381873240 (sast)","description":"The data in PASSWORD_SALT_ADMIN at /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java in line 88 may be sensitive, and it is exposed by an API at PASSWORD_SALT_ADMIN in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/missingac/MissingFunctionACUsers.java at line 88.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Session Fixation - 9214120936485315712 (sast)","name":"Session Fixation","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Method welcome at line 63 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/controller/Welcome.java performs user authentication without terminating existing sessions. This may enable Session Fixation.\n\n","markdown":"Method welcome at line 63 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/controller/Welcome.java performs user authentication without terminating existing sessions. This may enable Session Fixation.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Method welcome at line 63 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/controller/Welcome.java performs user authentication without terminating existing sessions. This may enable Session Fixation.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Session Fixation","id":"Session Fixation - 9214120936485315712 (sast)","description":"Method welcome at line 63 of /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/container/controller/Welcome.java performs user authentication without terminating existing sessions. This may enable Session Fixation.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-41234 (sca)","name":"Cve202541234","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"In Spring Framework, versions 6.0.x through 6.0.28, 6.1.x through 6.1.20, 6.2.x through 6.2.7, and 7.x through 7.0.0-m5, an application is vulnerable to a Reflected File Download (RFD) attack when it sets a Content-Disposition header with a non-ASCII charset, where the filename attribute is derived from user-supplied input.\n\nSpecifically, an application is vulnerable when all the following are true:\n\n  1. The header is prepared with org.springframework.http.ContentDisposition.\n  2. The filename is set via ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String, Charset).\n  3. The value for the filename is derived from user-supplied input.\n  4. The application does not sanitize the user-supplied input.\n  5. The downloaded content of the response is injected with malicious commands by the attacker (see RFD paper reference for details).\n\nAn application is not vulnerable if any of the following is true:\n\n  1. The application does not set a Content-Disposition response header.\n  2. The header is not prepared with org.springframework.http.ContentDisposition.\n  3. The filename is set via one of:  ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String), or ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String, ASCII)\n  4. The filename is not derived from user-supplied input.\n  5. The filename is derived from user-supplied input but sanitized by the application.\n  6. The attacker cannot inject malicious content in the downloaded content of the response.","markdown":"In Spring Framework, versions 6.0.x through 6.0.28, 6.1.x through 6.1.20, 6.2.x through 6.2.7, and 7.x through 7.0.0-m5, an application is vulnerable to a Reflected File Download (RFD) attack when it sets a Content-Disposition header with a non-ASCII charset, where the filename attribute is derived from user-supplied input.\n\nSpecifically, an application is vulnerable when all the following are true:\n\n  1. The header is prepared with org.springframework.http.ContentDisposition.\n  2. The filename is set via ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String, Charset).\n  3. The value for the filename is derived from user-supplied input.\n  4. The application does not sanitize the user-supplied input.\n  5. The downloaded content of the response is injected with malicious commands by the attacker (see RFD paper reference for details).\n\nAn application is not vulnerable if any of the following is true:\n\n  1. The application does not set a Content-Disposition response header.\n  2. The header is not prepared with org.springframework.http.ContentDisposition.\n  3. The filename is set via one of:  ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String), or ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String, ASCII)\n  4. The filename is not derived from user-supplied input.\n  5. The filename is derived from user-supplied input but sanitized by the application.\n  6. The attacker cannot inject malicious content in the downloaded content of the response."},"fullDescription":{"text":"In Spring Framework, versions 6.0.x through 6.0.28, 6.1.x through 6.1.20, 6.2.x through 6.2.7, and 7.x through 7.0.0-m5, an application is vulnerable to a Reflected File Download (RFD) attack when it sets a Content-Disposition header with a non-ASCII charset, where the filename attribute is derived from user-supplied input.\n\nSpecifically, an application is vulnerable when all the following are true:\n\n  1. The header is prepared with org.springframework.http.ContentDisposition.\n  2. The filename is set via ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String, Charset).\n  3. The value for the filename is derived from user-supplied input.\n  4. The application does not sanitize the user-supplied input.\n  5. The downloaded content of the response is injected with malicious commands by the attacker (see RFD paper reference for details).\n\nAn application is not vulnerable if any of the following is true:\n\n  1. The application does not set a Content-Disposition response header.\n  2. The header is not prepared with org.springframework.http.ContentDisposition.\n  3. The filename is set via one of:  ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String), or ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String, ASCII)\n  4. The filename is not derived from user-supplied input.\n  5. The filename is derived from user-supplied input but sanitized by the application.\n  6. The attacker cannot inject malicious content in the downloaded content of the response."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202541234","id":"CVE-2025-41234 (sca)","description":"In Spring Framework, versions 6.0.x through 6.0.28, 6.1.x through 6.1.20, 6.2.x through 6.2.7, and 7.x through 7.0.0-m5, an application is vulnerable to a Reflected File Download (RFD) attack when it sets a Content-Disposition header with a non-ASCII charset, where the filename attribute is derived from user-supplied input.\n\nSpecifically, an application is vulnerable when all the following are true:\n\n  1. The header is prepared with org.springframework.http.ContentDisposition.\n  2. The filename is set via ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String, Charset).\n  3. The value for the filename is derived from user-supplied input.\n  4. The application does not sanitize the user-supplied input.\n  5. The downloaded content of the response is injected with malicious commands by the attacker (see RFD paper reference for details).\n\nAn application is not vulnerable if any of the following is true:\n\n  1. The application does not set a Content-Disposition response header.\n  2. The header is not prepared with org.springframework.http.ContentDisposition.\n  3. The filename is set via one of:  ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String), or ContentDisposition.Builder#filename(String, ASCII)\n  4. The filename is not derived from user-supplied input.\n  5. The filename is derived from user-supplied input but sanitized by the application.\n  6. The attacker cannot inject malicious content in the downloaded content of the response.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"CVE-2019-11358 (sca)","name":"Cve201911358","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"jQuery before 3.4.0, as used in Drupal, Backdrop CMS, and other products, mishandles jQuery.extend(true, {}, ...) because of Object.prototype pollution. If an unsanitized source object contained an enumerable __proto__ property, it could extend the native Object.prototype.","markdown":"jQuery before 3.4.0, as used in Drupal, Backdrop CMS, and other products, mishandles jQuery.extend(true, {}, ...) because of Object.prototype pollution. If an unsanitized source object contained an enumerable __proto__ property, it could extend the native Object.prototype."},"fullDescription":{"text":"jQuery before 3.4.0, as used in Drupal, Backdrop CMS, and other products, mishandles jQuery.extend(true, {}, ...) because of Object.prototype pollution. If an unsanitized source object contained an enumerable __proto__ property, it could extend the native Object.prototype."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve201911358","id":"CVE-2019-11358 (sca)","description":"jQuery before 3.4.0, as used in Drupal, Backdrop CMS, and other products, mishandles jQuery.extend(true, {}, ...) because of Object.prototype pollution. If an unsanitized source object contained an enumerable __proto__ property, it could extend the native Object.prototype.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"Apt Get Install Pin Version Not Defined - 965a08d7-ef86-4f14-8792-4a3b2098937e [Taken from query_id] (kics)","name":"Apt Get Install Pin Version Not Defined","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"When installing a package, its pin version should be defined Value: Package 'nano' does not have version defined Excepted value: Package 'nano' has version defined","markdown":"When installing a package, its pin version should be defined \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eValue:\u003c/strong\u003e Package 'nano' does not have version defined \u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExcepted value:\u003c/strong\u003e Package 'nano' has version defined"},"fullDescription":{"text":"When installing a package, its pin version should be defined Value: Package 'nano' does not have version defined Excepted value: Package 'nano' has version defined"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Apt Get Install Pin Version Not Defined","id":"Apt Get Install Pin Version Not Defined - 965a08d7-ef86-4f14-8792-4a3b2098937e [Taken from query_id] (kics)","description":"When installing a package, its pin version should be defined Value: Package 'nano' does not have version defined Excepted value: Package 'nano' has version defined","tags":["security","checkmarx","kics"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-48924 (sca)","name":"Cve202548924","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Uncontrolled Recursion vulnerability in Apache Commons Lang. The methods `ClassUtils.getClass(...)` can `throwStackOverflowError` on very long inputs. Because an error is usually not handled by applications and libraries, a `StackOverflowError` could cause an application to stop. Users are recommended to upgrade to version 3.18.0, which fixes the issue. This issue affects commons-lang:commons-lang versions 2.0 through 2.6, and org.apache.commons:commons-lang3 versions 3.0 through 3.17.0.","markdown":"Uncontrolled Recursion vulnerability in Apache Commons Lang. The methods `ClassUtils.getClass(...)` can `throwStackOverflowError` on very long inputs. Because an error is usually not handled by applications and libraries, a `StackOverflowError` could cause an application to stop. Users are recommended to upgrade to version 3.18.0, which fixes the issue. This issue affects commons-lang:commons-lang versions 2.0 through 2.6, and org.apache.commons:commons-lang3 versions 3.0 through 3.17.0."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Uncontrolled Recursion vulnerability in Apache Commons Lang. The methods `ClassUtils.getClass(...)` can `throwStackOverflowError` on very long inputs. Because an error is usually not handled by applications and libraries, a `StackOverflowError` could cause an application to stop. Users are recommended to upgrade to version 3.18.0, which fixes the issue. This issue affects commons-lang:commons-lang versions 2.0 through 2.6, and org.apache.commons:commons-lang3 versions 3.0 through 3.17.0."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202548924","id":"CVE-2025-48924 (sca)","description":"Uncontrolled Recursion vulnerability in Apache Commons Lang. The methods `ClassUtils.getClass(...)` can `throwStackOverflowError` on very long inputs. Because an error is usually not handled by applications and libraries, a `StackOverflowError` could cause an application to stop. Users are recommended to upgrade to version 3.18.0, which fixes the issue. This issue affects commons-lang:commons-lang versions 2.0 through 2.6, and org.apache.commons:commons-lang3 versions 3.0 through 3.17.0.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-53864 (sca)","name":"Cve202553864","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Connect2id Nimbus JOSE + JWT allows a remote attacker to cause a Denial-of-Service (DoS) via a deeply nested JSON object supplied in a JWT claim set, because of uncontrolled recursion. NOTE: This is independent of the Gson 2.11.0 issue because the Connect2id product could have checked the JSON object nesting depth, regardless of what limits (if any) were imposed by Gson. This issue affects `com.nimbusds:nimbus-jose-jwt` versions 9.24 through 10.0.1.","markdown":"Connect2id Nimbus JOSE + JWT allows a remote attacker to cause a Denial-of-Service (DoS) via a deeply nested JSON object supplied in a JWT claim set, because of uncontrolled recursion. NOTE: This is independent of the Gson 2.11.0 issue because the Connect2id product could have checked the JSON object nesting depth, regardless of what limits (if any) were imposed by Gson. This issue affects `com.nimbusds:nimbus-jose-jwt` versions 9.24 through 10.0.1."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Connect2id Nimbus JOSE + JWT allows a remote attacker to cause a Denial-of-Service (DoS) via a deeply nested JSON object supplied in a JWT claim set, because of uncontrolled recursion. NOTE: This is independent of the Gson 2.11.0 issue because the Connect2id product could have checked the JSON object nesting depth, regardless of what limits (if any) were imposed by Gson. This issue affects `com.nimbusds:nimbus-jose-jwt` versions 9.24 through 10.0.1."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202553864","id":"CVE-2025-53864 (sca)","description":"Connect2id Nimbus JOSE + JWT allows a remote attacker to cause a Denial-of-Service (DoS) via a deeply nested JSON object supplied in a JWT claim set, because of uncontrolled recursion. NOTE: This is independent of the Gson 2.11.0 issue because the Connect2id product could have checked the JSON object nesting depth, regardless of what limits (if any) were imposed by Gson. This issue affects `com.nimbusds:nimbus-jose-jwt` versions 9.24 through 10.0.1.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"Reversible One Way Hash - 7875786759696254599 (sast)","name":"Reversible One Way Hash","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The application is using a weak hashing primitive getInstance, in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/cryptography/HashingAssignment.java at line 102\n\n","markdown":"The application is using a weak hashing primitive getInstance, in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/cryptography/HashingAssignment.java at line 102\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The application is using a weak hashing primitive getInstance, in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/cryptography/HashingAssignment.java at line 102\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Reversible One Way Hash","id":"Reversible One Way Hash - 7875786759696254599 (sast)","description":"The application is using a weak hashing primitive getInstance, in /WebGoat-main/src/main/java/org/owasp/webgoat/lessons/cryptography/HashingAssignment.java at line 102\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Use of Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm - 15434822379289186737 (sast)","name":"Use of Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm","helpUri":"ht